  "type": "mcq",
  "stem": "<p class=\"stem_paragraph \">How many solutions exist to the equation shown above?</p>\n",
  "answerOptions": [
    {
      "id": "a",
      "content": "<p class=\"choice_paragraph \">None</p>\n"
    },
    {
      "id": "b",
      "content": "<p class=\"choice_paragraph \">Exactly 1</p>\n"
    },
    {
      "id": "c",
      "content": "<p class=\"choice_paragraph \">Exactly 3</p>\n"
    },
    {
      "id": "d",
      "content": "<p class=\"choice_paragraph \">Infinitely many</p>\n"
    }
  ],
  "keys": [
    "b"
  ],
  "rationale": "<p>Choice B is correct. Subtracting 4 from each side of the given equation yields <span class=\"math-container\"><img align=\"middle\" role=\"math\" class=\"math-img\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" alt=\"6 equals 2 x\"></span>, or <span class=\"italic\"><span class=\"math-container\"><img align=\"middle\" role=\"math\" class=\"math-img\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" alt=\"x equals 3\"></span></span>, so the equation has a unique solution of <span class=\"math-container\"><img align=\"middle\" role=\"math\" class=\"math-img\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" alt=\"x equals 3\"></span>.<p>Choice A is incorrect. Since 3 is a value of <span class=\"italic\">x</span> that satisfies the given equation, the equation has at least 1 solution. Choice C is incorrect. Linear equations can have 0, 1, or infinitely many solutions; no linear equation has exactly 3 solutions. Choice D is incorrect. If a linear equation has infinitely many solutions, it can be reduced to <span class=\"math-container\"><img align=\"middle\" role=\"math\" class=\"math-img\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" alt=\"0 equals 0\"></span>. This equation reduces to <span class=\"math-container\"><img align=\"middle\" role=\"math\" class=\"math-img\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" alt=\"x equals 3\"></span>, so there is only 1 solution.</p><p>&nbsp;</p></p>\n",
